<tt>Sun Mar  9  7:35:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Could you imagine someone saying that the American leaders sent 57,600 Americans to their deaths because they were so moved by the plight of the South Vietnamese? Could you imagine Kennedy, Johnson, Nixon, or MacNamera thinking &quot;God, I feel so sorry for those poor South Vietnamese. My heart just aches when I watch them on television. There must be some way I can help them. I'd be willing to send Americans to die just to help those poor people&quot;? Could you imagine someone seriously suggesting that the American leaders were motivated by compassion for the South Vietnamese people? Could you imagine someone saying that Johnson and Nixon sent Americans to their deaths because they personally couldn't stand the fact that poor people in a distant part of the world were suffering? Do you think anyone believes that? Do you think Johnson thought, &quot;As a politician, I'm sending Americans to die in a distant foreign war because I can't stand to watch people elsewhere in the world suffer&quot;? Why did that inability to watch people elsewhere in the world suffer, not cause him to send Americans to die in Burma, Indonesia, or Nigeria? If we were motivated by sympathy for the Vietnamese people, why were we not motivated by sympathy for the Nigerian people? Why were the Vietnamese people worthy of such hardship and sacrifice on our part whereas the Nigerian people were not worthy of this? Why didn't the same altruistic compassion that caused us to die for the poor Vietnamese people not cause us to go to war and die for the poor Nigerian people? Why were the South Vietnamese specifically singled out as being worthy of having 57,600 Americans die on their behalf, whereas the people of Burma, Indonesia, Nigeria, etc. were not? If you were truly motivated by love of your fellow man, you wouldn't care what country someone was a citizen of. Of course, the American leaders were never moved to action out of sympathy for the Vietnamese people. They wanted to establish a puppet government loyal to Washington. From 1965 to 1977, Indonesia was a military dictatorship ruled by General Suharto who slaughtered one million of his own citizens. Why did the altruistic compassion that caused us to send 57,600 Americans to die on behalf of the South Vietnamese not cause us to lift a single finger to help the one million people murdered by the dictator of Indonesia? If Johnson was incapable of watching poor people elsewhere in the world suffer, why was he capable of watching people in Burma, Nigeria, and all over the world suffer? His inability to watch poor South Vietnamese suffer did not prevent him from watching people in Burma, Nigeria, and all over the world being slaughtered. The reason the South Vietnamese were singled out as being worthy of our &quot;compassion&quot; was because it hung in the balance whether that tiny country would be loyal to the United States.<br><br>
The next part of your post is baffling. Are you suddenly agreeing with me that the U.S. cared nothing about the South Vietnamese? I said, &quot;if we were truly motivated by altruistic compassion, we would not view the plight of the Vietnamese to warrant our intervention, and simultaneously consider the plight of the Nigerians to not warrant our intervention.&quot; Then to this, you replied, &quot;I don't know. Why didn't we?&quot; If you're admitting the American intervention in Vietnam was not motivated by altruistic compassion for the South Vietnamese, I'm pleasantly surprised, but I must also admit that it comes as something of a shock. You didn't strike me as the sort of person who could be converted to my side so quickly. Perhaps I underestimate my own powers of persuasion. You actually agreed with me that the U.S. cared nothing about the South Vietnamese. I asked, &quot;If we were motivated by compassion, why didn't that same compassion motivate us to help the Nigerians&quot; and then you said, &quot;Yeah, why didn't it?&quot; This is amazing. I can't believe that I converted you to my side so easily. You said that our intervention in Vietnam couldn't have been motivated by compassion, since if it had been, that same compassion would have motivated us to intervene in Nigeria. What makes this baffling is that the rest of your post lacks the tone of someone who agrees with me. It's like throughout most of your post, you're trying to say that the reason the American leaders sent 57,600 Americans to their deaths is because they couldn't stand to think of South Vietnamese suffering. Then in the middle of all of this, you inexplicably insert a passage admitting that of course we were not motivated by compassion. Did you accidently slip up and admit what you know to be the truth? If you were trying to say that we were motivated by compassion, then why would you include the passage admitting that of course we were not motivated by compassion. If you were admitting that we were not motivated by compassion, then why would you fill up the rest of your post with a claim that we were motivated by compassion. You didn't notice this juxtaposition? At least I got you to admit the truth, however confusing your overall post. I said, &quot;If we were motivated by altruistic compassion, we would not view the plight of the Vietnamese to warrant our intervention, and simultaneously consider the plight of the Nigerians to not warrant our intervention&quot;, and then you said, &quot;I don't know. Why didn't we?&quot;<br><br>
The reason we did not intervene in Nigeria is because from the point of view of the American government, we already &quot;owned&quot; Nigeria. We didn't have to go in and install a pro-American government because the current dictatorship was already a pro-American government. The conflicts in Somalia, Bosnia, Haiti, and Kuwait occurred after the end of the Cold War, when we would pretend to rule the whole world with a casual wave of the hand. Besides, we did invade Haiti and Kuwait, and established pro-American governments. Throughout the Cold War, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia already had pro-American governments. You compare a famine with the slaughter in Nigeria? There's a big difference between being indirectly responsible for deaths caused by economic policies, and going out there and actually killing people.<br>
Nothing could make &quot;Nigeria look like Disneyland&quot;. That is an outrageous statement trivializing the suffering and oppression of people, which you claim to care about. You say, &quot;I lost your point&quot;. The point is that if compassion motivated us to help the South Vietnamese, why didn't it motivate us to help people elsewhere in the world? In other words, of course the American involvement in Vietnam was not motivated by compassion for the South Vietnamese. I was not advocating a position on whether &quot;we should do more, do less, do nothing?&quot;<br><br>
According to some estimates, there were only about 20,000 Iraqi combat deaths. I've read other objective estimates that state that least 100,000 were killed. I wish I had the report that I saw in front of me. This does remind me of one side story regarding these figures. During the 1992 campaign George Bush was afraid that the high civilian casualties and the large number of children killed might hurt his re-election chances. He thought that it might tarnish his image for such high civilian casualties and children casualties, which they casually referred to as &quot;collateral damage&quot; to be reported in the news. It's standard practice for the Pentagon to release the figures but Bush stepped and suppressed the information, preventing its release. However, a woman working at the Pentagon, and who happened to be a Democrat, leaked it to the press. As it turned out, the attempt to suppress the information was a bigger story than the figures themselves. If he had let them be released normally, it would have been in the back pages. Since he tried to prevent their release, it made the headlines. However, I don't think that anyone voted for Clinton because of that issue. George Bush's action might also imply that he himself had some guilt over what he had done. The vast majority of the &quot;guys in uniform&quot; had been drafted after the invasion of Kuwait in anticipation of the American attack. The elite Republican Guard, of course got away.<br><br>
In 1970, Allende became the first president democratically elected on a Marxist program. On Sept 11, 1973, there was a military coup, and Allende was killed. The CIA was behind the coup. You say, &quot;Did we encourage them-yes, did we do it-no&quot;. Our &quot;encouragement&quot; involved planning it, and financing it. How involved does your &quot;encouragement&quot; have to be before you're &quot;doing it&quot;? The joke you tell prooves my point. No one would make up a joke about the U.S. being responsible for all the problems of Latin America, unless we were responsible for many problems in Latin America. It wouldn't be funny otherwise. Would someone make up a joke about Switzerland or Quebec being responsible for all the problems in Latin America?<br><br>
We trained some of the people involved in the death squads of El Salvador. You may not like that fact. We encouraged the dictatorship to do everything possible to defeat the rebels. We gave them money and weapons. I remember once at a press conference, a black woman asked Bush, &quot;Are we killing priests in El Salvador?&quot; and he respnded &quot;No, we are not.&quot;<br>
That was a lie. We may not have pulled the trigger but we knew about it and did nothing to stop it. We strongly supported those who pulled the trigger. The Duarte dictatorship massacred whole villages suspected of being sympathetic to the rebels, and targeted Catholic clergy which they considered leftist. They would have beeb less successful in their terror without the obsessive backing of the United States. To say, &quot;the situation would have been very much worse if the U.S. hadn't stepped in&quot; is such a horrible statement. We were supporting the people doing the massacres. It's as if we supported Hitler, and then said that the genocide would have been much worse if he hadn't supported him.<br><br>
The Mexican-American War was caused by the American annexation of Texas in 1845. Are you saying that when we unilaterally declared Texas to be part of the United States, that the Mexicans already in Texas were then officially foreigners &quot;invading&quot; our country. David Thoreau heralded as heroes, those soldiers who refused to fight. The Mexican-American War as a land grab, like when Iraq invaded Kuwait. This is a sad chapter in our history. American schools usually jump over it because it's so shameful.<br><br>
Of course the United States did not want to enter World War I. That's why we didn't enter it until the very end. I don't blame Americans for not wanting to enter the war. They didn't want their people to be killed. British and French pressure alone would not have brought us into the war. What turned the tide of American opinion was the sinking of the Lusitania off the coast of southern Ireland on May 8, 1915, which though a British ocean liner, carried many Americans. The attack, coming only three years after the Titanic, seemed like a delibrate re-enactment of a natural disaster, and outraged Americans. The Lusitania was carrying munitions, and Germany did not violate international law in sinking the ship. However American sensitivity was deeply violated, and so we entered the war. We did not enter the war because we were fighting for freedom and democracy. If we cared about that, we would have entered the war in the beginning instead of the very end. For years, Britain and France begged us to enter the war, but we were resolutely against it. <br><br>
Similarly, from 1939 to 1941, Churchill begged Roosevelt to enter the war, but he was also resolutely against it. Americans were very afraid that they might be dragged into World War II. Of course they didn't want to enter the war. It's only when we ourselves were attacked that we entered the war. There is absolutely no indication that we would have entered the war otherwise. Before Pearl Habor, we were digging in our heels. Nobody in the U.S. wanted to enter the war. If we had such high minded idealism, we would have entered the war in the very beginning, just to fight for democracy. If Japan hadn't bombed Pearl Habor, we wouldn't have entered the war except in the unlikely chance that Germany was ever in a position to attack the United States. The only reason we declared war on Germany is because Germany declared war on us.<br><br>
Grenada was not about &quot;rescuing&quot; anything other than Reagan's image.<br><br>
From about the 16th Century to World War II, the most powerful nations in the world were the European Colonial Empires, Britain, France, and Spain, and there was continual rivalry between them. From 1945 to about 1990, the most powerful nations in the world were the superpowers, and there was continual rivalry between them. This was called the Cold War. If someone were to say, &quot;Britain won the European Colonial Empires&quot;, that would be a completely meaningless statement. It's not even grammatically correct. Yet there are people who say, &quot;The United States won the Cold War&quot;, which is equivalent. There are people who say, &quot;___ won the ___&quot; where the second blank is a period of history, and the first blank is the name of one of the dominant powers at that time. That doesn't mean anything. The dominant powers are an aspect of whatever time period you're talking about. When the historical period comes to an end, the countries in question stop being dominant powers. The existance of the superpowers was an aspect of the Cold War. When the Cold War ceased to exist, the superpowers ceased to exist. The United States stopped being a superpower with the end of the Cold War. We forget that during the Cold War, the countries of Western Europe were simply our satellites within the American Bloc. We occupied Western Europe with U.S. troops, and the people living in those countries, such as West Germany, were not enthusiastic about our presence. Margaret Thatcher was harshly criticized for being a lapdog for the U.S. People in Britain complained that the United States considered Britain to be a giant American aircraft carrier. The power of the United States was derived entirely from the Cold War. The whole premise was &quot;you have to submit to us because you need our protection of the Soviets&quot;. When the Cold War ended, and people realized that the Soviets were never a threat to them, we could no longer use that argument. The power of the United States evaporated. On what grounds would you claim that today the United States is more powerful than Britain, France, Japan, or Europe as a whole? During the Cold War, our dominance went without saying. During the Cold War, the superpowers employed a very old trick to rule their satellites. How did Alfred the Great conquer the seven Saxon kingdoms? He went to the other Saxon kings, and convinced them that they needed his protection from the Danes. Therefore the other kings allowed his troops in their kingdoms voluntarily. He got them to pledge subservience to him. This is exactly what the United States did. This is what the superpowers did during the Cold War. When the satellites saw through this ruse, they could no longer use that argument. When the Cold War ceased to exist, the superpowers ceased to exist. Therefore the United States is no longer a superpower. We didn't win anything. We lost tremendously. Our power in the world is greatly diminished. You saw how the Europeans took the lead in Bosnia, and sent in peacekeepers when we did not. You saw how France took the lead in providing relief to Rwandan refugees. 
